[William F. Giauque]]''', B.S. 1920, Ph.D. 1922 â Nobel laureate (1949, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Chemistry]]),<ref>{{Cite document|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1949/giauque-bio.html|title=Nobel Lectures, Chemistry 1942â1962|publisher=[[Elsevier Publishing Company]]|location=[[Amsterdam]]|year=1964|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> ''"for his contributions in the field of [[chemical thermodynamics]], particularly concerning the behaviour of substances at extremely low temperatures"'' *[[Carol W. Greider]], Ph.D. 1987 â Nobel laureate (2009, Medicine)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2009/|title=The Nobel Prize in Medicine 2009|date=|publisher=[[Nobel Prize]]Foundation}}</ref> ''"for the discovery of how [[chromosomes]] are protected by [[telomeres]] and the enzyme [[telomerase]]"''; Daniel Nathans Professor and the Director of Molecular Biology and Genetics at the [[Johns Hopkins University]] *[[David Gross]], Ph.D. 1966 â Nobel laureate (2004, Physics),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/2004/gross-autobio.html|author=[[David Gross]]|title=Autobiography|publisher=[[Nobel Foundation]]|year=2004}}</ref> ''"for the discovery of [[asymptotic freedom]] in the theory of the [[strong interaction]]"'' *[[Alan Heeger]], Ph.D. 1961 â Nobel laureate (2000, Chemistry),<ref>{{Cite document|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/2000/heeger-autobio.html|title= Les Prix Nobel. The Nobel Prizes 2000|author=Tore FrÃ¤ngsmyr, editor|publisher=[[Nobel Foundation]]|location=Stockholm|year=2001|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> ''"for the discovery and development of [[conductive polymers]]"'' *[[Daniel Kahneman]], Ph.D. 1961 â Nobel laureate (2002, Economics),<ref>{{Cite document|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/economics/laureates/2002/kahneman-autobio.html|title= Les Prix Nobel. The Nobel Prizes 2002|author=Tore FrÃ¤ngsmyr, editor|publisher=[[Nob