==Turing Award laureates== The [[Turing Award]] is considered to be the "[[Nobel Prize]]" of [[computer science]]. *[[Leonard Adleman]] B.A. 1968 (mathematics), Ph.D. 1976,<ref>{{cite news|title=SCIENTIST AT WORK: Leonard Adleman; Hitting the High Spots Of Computer Theory|author=Gina Kolata|publisher=New York Times|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9500EEDD1F39F930A25751C1A962958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print|date=1994-12-13}}</ref> the "A" in the [[RSA (algorithm)|RSA]] encryption algorithm for computer security, co-recipient of the Turing Award in 2002 for the ''"ingenious contribution for making [[public-key cryptography]] useful in practice.''". *[[Douglas C. Engelbart]], B.Eng. 1952,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bootstrap.org/chronicle/cv.html |title=Welcome - bootstrap.org Redirect - Doug Engelbart Institute |publisher=Bootstrap.org |date= |accessdate=2011-08-02}}</ref> Ph.D. 1955 â Inventor of the [[computer mouse]], recipient of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 2000, pioneer in [[hypertext]] and networked computers, recipient of the 1997 Turing Award ''"for an inspiring vision of the future of interactive computing and the invention of key technologies to help realize this vision."'' *[[Jim Gray (computer scientist)|Jim Gray]], B.S. 1966, Ph.D. 1969 â Recipient of the 2001 Turing Award<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/may/30/business/fi-jimgray30|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=Berkeley event to honor missing scientist Jim Gray|author= Michelle Quinn|date=2008-05-30}}</ref> ''"for seminal contributions to [[database]] and [[transaction processing]] research and technical leadership in system implementation."'' *[[Butler Lampson]], Ph.D. 1967 â computer scientist, founding member of [[Xerox PARC]], major contributor to the development of the personal computer, and recipient of the 1992 Turing Award<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ieee.org/portal/pages/about/awards/bios/2001vonneumann.html|title=Butler W. Lampson|publisher=[[IEEE]]}}</ref> ''"for contributions to the development of distributed, personal computing environments and the technology for their implementation: [[workstation]]s, [[computer network|networks]], [[operating system]]s, programming systems, [[computer display|displays]], [[computer security|security]] and [[word processor|document publishing]]."'' *[[Barbara Liskov]], B.A. 1961 â first woman in the United States to earn a Ph.D. in Computer Science (in 1968 at Stanford), creator of [[CLU programming language|CLU]], professor at [[MIT]]; recipient of the 2008 Turing Award<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/business/technology/articles/2009/03/10/top_prize_in_computing_goes_to_mit_professor/|title=Top prize in computing goes to MIT professor|publisher=The Boston Globe|date=2009-03-10|author=Robert Weisman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2009/turing-liskov-0310.html|title=Barbara Liskov wins Turing Award|publisher=[[MIT]]|date=2009-03-10}}</ref> "''for contributions to practical and theoretical foundations of programming language and system design, especially related to data abstraction, [[fault tolerance]], and [[distributed computing]].''" *[[Dana Scott]], B.S. 1954 â computer scientist, co-recipient of the 1976 Turing Award with [[Michael O. Rabin]], for ''"the joint paper (with Rabin) "Finite Automata and Their Decision Problem", which introduced the idea of [[nondeterministic machine]]s, which has proved to be an enormously valuable concept. Their (Scott & Rabin) classic paper has been a continuous source of inspiration for subsequent work in this field''"; former Associate Professor of Math at UC Berkeley, professor emeritus at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] *[[Charles P. Thacker]], B.A. (physics) 1967<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerhistory.org/fellowawards/index.php?id=112|title=Fellow Awards â Charles Thacker|publisher=[[Computer History Museum]]|year=2007}}</ref> â [[Microsoft]] Technical Fellow, chief designer of the [[Alto (computer)|Alto]] computer at [[Xerox PARC]], co-inventor of [[Ethernet]], recipient of the [[IEEE]] [[John von Neumann]] Medal in 2007, recipient of the [[Draper Prize]] in 2004; recipient of the 2009 Turing Award<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[USA Today]]|title=Charles Thacker wins Turing Award, computing's 'Nobel prize'|author=Elizabeth Weise|date=2010-03-15|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/sciencefair/post/2010/03/charles-thacker-wins-turing-award-computings-nobel-prize/1}}</ref> "''for his pioneering design and realization of the [[Alto (computer)|Alto]], the first modern personal computer, and in addition for his contributions to the [[Ethernet]] and the [[Microsoft Tablet PC|Tablet PC]].''" *[[Ken Thompson]], B.S. EE 1965, M.S. EE 1966 â Co-creator of the [[Unix]] [[operating system]] and co-recipient of the 1983 Turing Award for the ''"development of generic operating systems theory and specifically for the implementation of the [[Unix|UNIX]] operating system."'' *[[Niklaus Wirth]], Ph.D. 1967 â computer scientist, creator of the [[Pascal programming language]], recipient of the 1984 Turing Award ''"for developing a sequence of innovative computer languages, [[Euler programming language|EULER]], [[Algol-W|ALGOL-W]], [[Modula|MODULA]] and [[Pascal (programming language)|Pascal]]."''
==Academy Award== *Mark Berger, B.A. 1964 â recipient of four Academy Awards for sound mixing and adjunct professor at UC Berkeley.<ref>{{cite web|title=UC Berkeley Professor Mixes Sound for Award Winning Films|author=Jawad Qadir|date=March 31, 2010|url=http://www.dailycal.org/article/108855|publisher=The Daily Californian}}</ref> *Tony DeRose, Ph.D. 1985 â Senior Scientist and leader of the Research Group at [[Pixar]] Animation Studios, recipient of a Scientific and Technical Academy Award in 2006 for work on surface representations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tinkering.exploratorium.edu/tony-derose/|title=Tony DeRose -The Tinkering Studio - Exploratorium|publisher=Exploratorium}}</ref> *[[Paul E. Debevec]], Ph.D. 1996 â Associate Driector of Graphics Research at the [[University of Southern California]]'s Institute for Creative Technologies, recipient of a Scientific and Technical Academy Award in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://innovations.coe.berkeley.edu/vol4-issue7-sept10/debevec|title=Man of a thousand faces|author=Rachel Shafer|publisher=Innovations|date=2010-09|volume=10|issue=7|publisher=College of Engineering, University of California, Berkeley}}</ref> for work used on the [[James Cameron]] film ''[[Avatar]]'', the [[Sam Raimi]] film ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'', and the [[Peter Jackson]] film ''[[King Kong]]''. *[[Charles H. Ferguson]], B.A. 1978 â recipient of an Academy Award for Best Documentary for ''[[Inside Job (film)|Inside Job]]'' (2010),<ref name="Andrew Pulver">{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2011/feb/28/inside-job-best-documentary-oscar|publisher=The Guardian ([[United Kingdom]])|date=2011-02-28|author=Andrew Pulver|title=Oscars 2011: Inside Job banks best documentary award}}</ref> Academy Award nomination<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979395|title=Academy Awards nominations list|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2008-01-22|author=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] Staff}}</ref> for the documentary film ''[[No End in Sight]]'' (2007),<ref name="Michelle Meyers">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/How-filmmaking-is-like-launching-a-start-up/2008-1026_3-6201857.html|title=How filmmaking is like launching a start-up|author=Michelle Meyers|date=2007-08-10|publisher=[[CNet]]}}</ref> former fellow at the [[Brookings Institution]], lifelong member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], co-founder of [[Vermeer Technologies Incorporated]] (acquired by [[Microsoft]] for $133 million<ref name="Steve Hamm">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/1999/99_47/b3656050.htm|publisher=[[BusinessWeek]]|title=Caught Between a Rock and [[Bill Gates]]|author=Steve Hamm|date=1999-11-22}}</ref>), founder and president of Representational Pictures *[[Edith Head]], B.A. in French 1918<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiritus-temporis.com/edith-head/ |title=Edith Head â Biography of Edith Head |publisher=Spiritus-temporis.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-02}}</ref> â costume designer, recipient of eight Academy Awards<ref name="Britannica_EdithHead">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/258059/Edith-Head|publisher=[[EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica]] Online|accessdate=2009-02-14|title=EdithHead}}</ref> and nominated for 34 [[Academy Awards]]<ref name="Britannica_EdithHead"/> *[[Chris Innis]], B.A. (film studies) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.avid.com/blogs/buzz/archive/2010/03/04/the-hurt-locker-editor-chris-innis-to-guest-blog-on-avid-industry-buzz-bringing-you-all-the-excitement-leading-up-to-the-oscars.aspx|publisher=[[Avid]]|date=2010-03-07|title=The Hurt Locker Editor Christ Innis to guest blog on Avid Industry Buzz}}</ref> â recipient of the Academy Award for Best Film Editing (for ''[[The Hurt Locker]]'' (2010))<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/digital/2011-oscar-watch-science-technology-academy-award-winners|title=2011 OScars: PM Picks the Winners for the Sci-Tech Academy Awards|author=Steve Rousseau|publisher=[[Popular Mechanics]]}}</ref> *[[Joe Letteri]], B.A. 1981<ref>{{cite journal|journal=California Magazine|date=June 2003|title=Talk of the Gown â Blues in the News|publisher=Cal Alumni Association}} {{cite web|url=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20030629032723/http://www.alumni.berkeley.edu/Alumni/Cal_Monthly/June_2003/Talk_of_the_Gown.asp|publisher=California Magazine and the Cal Alumni Association|date=June 2003|title=Talk of the Gown â Blues in the News}}</ref> â recipient of four Academy Awards for Best Visual Special Effects in films directed by [[James Cameron]] (''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'') and [[Peter Jackson]] (''[[King Kong (2005 film)|King Kong]]'', ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Two Towers|The Two Towers]]'' and ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King|The Return of the King]]'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Beaver County native wins fourth Oscar for visual effects|author=Sandra Fischione Donovan|publisher=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|date=March 12, 2010}}</ref> *[[Freida Lee Mock]], B.A. 1961 â documentary filmmaker, recipient of the Academy Award for Best Documentary in 1995 (for ''[[Maya Lin: A Strong Clear Vision]]'') *[[Gregory Peck]], B.A. 1939 â actor, recipient of the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for Best Actor for portrayal of [[Atticus Finch]] in ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962), nominated for the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] four other times; served as president of the [[Screen Actors Guild]] *[[Walter Plunkett]], B.A. 1923 â costume designer, recipient of the [[Academy Award]] for Best Costume Design for the 1951 film ''[[An American in Paris (film)|An American in Paris]]'' starring [[Gene Kelly]]
