==Wolf Prize== *[[George Feher]], B.S. 1950, M.S. 1951, Ph.D. 1954<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aip.org/history/acap/biographies/bio.jsp?feherg|publisher=[[American Institute of Physics]]|title = Array of Contemporary American Physicists â George Feher}}</ref> â inventor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wolffund.org.il/full.asp?id=153|title=THE 2006/7 WOLF FOUNDATION PRIZE IN CHEMISTRY|publisher=[[Wolf Foundation]]|year=2007}}</ref> of [[electron nuclear double resonance]] (ENDOR); professor at the [[University of California, San Diego]]; recipient of the [[Wolf Prize]] (Chemistry, 2006/2007)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/newsrel/science/wolfprize07.asp|date=2007-01-08|author=Kim McDonald|title=UC San Diego Professor Wins Wolf Prize in Chemistry|publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]]}}</ref> "''for the ingenious structural discoveries of the [[ribosome|ribosomal]] machinery of [[peptide]]-bond formation and the light-driven primary processes in [[photosynthesis]]''"<ref name="Chemistry">{{cite web|url=http://www.wolffund.org.il/cat.asp?id=15&cat_title=CHEMISTRY|publisher=[[Wolf Foundation]]|title= Chemistry}}</ref> *[[Bertrand Halperin]] Ph.D. 1965<ref>{{cite web|title= Prize Recipient â Bertrand I. Halperin|publisher=[[American Physical Society]]|url = http://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/prizerecipient.cfm?name=Bertrand%20I.%20Halperin&year=2001}}</ref> â Hollis Professor of Mathematics and Natural Philosophy at [[Harvard University]]; recipient of the Wolf Prize (Physics, 2002â2003) "''for key insights into the broad range of [[condensed matter]] physics... on two- dimensional melting, disordered systems and strongly interacting [[electrons]].''"<ref name="wolffundil">{{cite web|url=http://www.wolffund.org.il/cat.asp?id=25&cat_title=PHYSICS|publisher=[[Wolf Foundation]]|title= Physics }}</ref> *'''[[George Pimentel]]''', Ph.D. 1949<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/21/obituaries/george-c-pimentel-chemist-who-led-mars-study-was-67.html|publisher = New York Times|author = Glenn Fowler|title=George C. Pimentel; Chemist Who Led Mars Study Was 67|date=1989-06-21}}</ref> â professor at UC Berkeley (1949â1989); inventor of the [[chemical laser]] ; recipient of the Wolf Prize (Chemistry, 1982) for the "''development of [[matrix isolation|matrix isolation spectroscopy]] and for the discovery of [[photodissociation]] lasers and [[chemical laser]]s.''"<ref name="Chemistry"/> *[[Chien-Shiung Wu]], Ph.D. 1940<ref name="BobNelson_19970221">{{cite web|title = Famed Physicist Chien-Shiung Wu Dies at 84|url = http://www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol22/vol22_iss15/record2215.16.html |publisher= Columbia University Record |date= 1997-02-21|author = Bob Nelson}}</ref> â professor of physics at [[Columbia University]] (1940â1980) ;recipient of the Wolf Prize (Physics, 1978) "''for her explorations of the [[weak interaction]], helping establish the precise form and the non-conservation of parity for this natural force ''";<ref name="wolffundil"/> first female president of the [[American Physical Society]]<ref name="BobNelson_19970221"/> *[[Shing-Tung Yau]], Ph.D. 1971<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/652235/Shing-Tung-Yau|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]] Online|title = Shing-Tung Yau}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= SCIENTIST AT WORK â Shing-Tung Yau; The Emperor of Math|date = 2006-10-17|publisher= The New York Times|author=Dennis Overbye|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E7DB1E30F934A25753C1A9609C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all}}</ref> â (also listed in [[#Fields Medal|Fields Medal]]) professor of mathematics at [[Harvard University]]; [[Fields Medal]] laureate; recipient of the Wolf Prize (Mathematics, 2010) "''for his work in geometric analysis that has had a profound and dramatic impact on many areas of geometry and physics''"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wolffund.org.il/cat.asp?id=23&cat_title=MATHEMATICS|publisher=[[Wolf Foundation]]|title= Mathematics}}</ref>
==National Medal of Science== *[[Berni Alder]], BS 1947, MS 1948 - recipient of the 2009 [[National Medal of Science]]<ref name="2009_NationalMedalOfScience_Corten">{{cite web|url=http://grad.berkeley.edu/news/headlines/honors-awards/two-scientists-now-national-icons/|title=Two scientists, both with Berkeley graduate degrees, are now "national icons"|date=2010-04-07|author=Dick CortÃ©n|publisher=The Graduate magazine and the Graduate Division of the University of California, Berkeley }}</ref> ''"for establishing powerful computer methods useful for molecular dynamics simulations, conceiving and executing experimental shock-wave simulations to obtain properties of fluids and solids at very high pressures, and developing [[Monte Carlo method]]s for calculating the properties of matter from first principles, all of which contributed to major achievements in the science of [[condensed matter physics|condensed matter]]."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=5300000000450|title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - Berni Alder|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> *[[John N. Bahcall]], B.S. 1956, [[astrophysicist]], best known<ref name="Times2005_09_01">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,60-1758833,00.html|work=[[The Times]](United Kingdom)|date=2005-09-01|title=Obituaries â Professor John Bahcall | location=London | first1=December | last1=10}}</ref> for his work on the [[Standard Solar Model]] and the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]]<ref name="Times2005_09_01"/> in 1998 ''"for his fundamental contributions to areas of modern astrophysics ranging from [[solar neutrino]] physics to the structure of the [[Milky Way Galaxy]] to [[cosmology]], and for his leadership of the astronomical community, especially his tireless advocacy of the [[Hubble Space Telescope]]."'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=26 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - John N. Bahcall|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> recipient of the [[NASA Distinguished Public Service Medal]]<ref name="Times2005_09_01"/> in 1992, co-winner of the [[Enrico Fermi|Fermi award]] in 2003 *[[John W. Cahn]], Ph.D. 1953 â [[materials science|materials scientist]], recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1998 ''"for his pioneering work on [[thermodynamics]] and kinetics of [[phase transitions]] and [[diffusion]], on [[Phase (matter)#Interfacial phenomena|interfacial phenomena]], and for his contributions to the understanding of periodic and quasi-periodic structures."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=66 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - John W. Cahn|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> *[[Brent Dalrymple]], PhD 1963- recipient of the 2003 [[National Medal of Science]] ''"for his pioneering work in determining the [[Geomagnetic reversal#Geomagnetic polarity time scale|geomagnetic polarity reversal timescale]]; a discovery that led to the theory of [[plate tectonics]]."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=5000000000424|title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - G. Brent Dalrymple|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> *[[Henry Eyring]], Ph.D. 1927 â namesake of the [[Eyring equation]] ;Professor of Chemistry ([[Princeton University]]), dean of the [[University of Utah]] graduate school and recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1966 ''"for contributions to our understanding of the structure and properties of matter, especially for his creation of [[Transition state theory|absolute rate theory]], one of the sharpest tools in the study of rates of chemical reaction."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id= 123 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - Henry Eyring|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> *[[T.Y. Lin]], M.S. 1933 â Professor of [[Civil Engineering]], bridge builder, pioneering researcher and practitioner of [[prestressed concrete]], designed [[Moscone Center]], recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1986 ''"for his work as an engineer, teacher and author whose scientific analyses, technological innovation, and visionary designs have spanned the gulf not only between science and art, but also between technology and society."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=221|title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - T.Y. Lin|publisher=National Science Foundation}}</ref> *[[Susan Solomon]], M.S. 1979, Ph.D. 1981 â Senior Scientist, [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA), recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 2000 ''"for key scientific insights in explaining the cause of the Antarctic [[ozone depletion|Ozone hole]] and for advancing the understanding of the global ozone layer; for changing the direction of ozone research through her findings; and for exemplary service to worldwide public policy decisions and to the American public."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id= 332 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - Susan Solomon|publisher=National Science Foundation}}</ref> *[[JoAnne Stubbe]], PhD 1971 - recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 2008<ref name="2009_NationalMedalOfScience_Corten"/> ''"for her ground-breaking experiments establishing the mechanisms of [[ribonucleotide reductases]], polyester synthases, and natural product DNA cleavers compelling demonstrations of the power of chemical investigations to solve problems in biology."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id=5300000000457 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - JoAnne Stubbe]|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref> *[[Shing-Tung Yau]], Ph.D. 1971 â mathematician, recipient of the [[Fields Medal]] in 1982, recipient of the [[National Medal of Science]] in 1997 ''"for his fundamental contributions in mathematics and physics. Through his work, the understanding of basic geometric differential equations has been changed and he has expanded their role enormously within mathematics."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsf.gov/od/nms/recip_details.cfm?recip_id= 406 |title=The President's National Medal of Science: Recipient Details - Shing-Tung Yau|publisher=[[National Science Foundation]]}}</ref>
==National Medal of Technology== *[[Glen Culler]], BA Math 1951 â recipient of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 1999 ''"for pioneering innovations in multiple branches of computing, including early efforts in digital speech processing, invention of the first on-line system for interactive graphical mathematics computing and pioneering work on the [[ARPAnet]]"''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspto.gov/about/nmti/recipients/1999.jsp|title=The National Medal of Technology and Innovation Recipients - 1999 Laureates}}</ref> *[[Doug Engelbart]], B. Eng. 1952, Ph.D. 1965 â recipient of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 2000 ''"for creating the foundations of personal computing including continuous, real-time interaction based on [[cathode-ray tube]] displays and the [[mouse (computing)|mouse]], [[hypertext]] linking, text editing, on-line journals, shared-screen [[teleconferencing]], and remote collaborative work. More than any other person, he created the personal computing component of the computer revolution."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspto.gov/about/nmti/recipients/2000.jsp|title=The National Medal of Technology and Innovation Recipients - 2000 Laureates}}</ref> *[[Gordon Moore]], B.S. 1950 â co-founder of [[NASDAQ-100]] company [[Intel]], namesake and originator of [[Moore's Law]], co-founder of [[NASDAQ-100]] semiconductor manufacturing company [[Intel]], recipient of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 1990 ''"for his seminal leadership in bringing American industry the two major postwar innovations in microelectronics - large-scale integrated memory and the [[microprocessor]] - that have fueled the information revolution."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspto.gov/about/nmti/recipients/1990.jsp|title=The National Medal of Technology and Innovation Recipients - 1990 Laureates}}</ref> *[[Ken Thompson]], B.S. EE 1965, M.S. EE 1966 â Co-creator of the [[Unix]] [[operating system]] and co-recipient of the 1983 [[Turing Award]], co-recipient of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 1998 for the ''"invention of the [[UNIX]]Â® operating system and the [[C (programming language)|C programming language]], which together have led to enormous growth of an entire industry, thereby enhancing American leadership in the [[Information Age]]."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspto.gov/about/nmti/recipients/1998.jsp|title=The National Medal of Technology and Innovation Recipients - 1998 Laureates}}</ref> (also listed under [[#Turing Award laureates|Turing Award laureates section]]) *[[Steve Wozniak]], (class of 1976, BS EECS 1986)â co-founder of [[NASDAQ-100]] computer manufacturing company [[Apple Inc.]], co-recipient (with [[Steve Jobs]]) of the [[National Medal of Technology]] in 1985 for the ''"development and introduction of the [[personal computer]] which has sparked the birth of a new industry extending the power of the computer to individual users."''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uspto.gov/about/nmti/recipients/1985.jsp|title=The National Medal of Technology and Innovation Recipients - 1985 Laureates}}</ref> (also listed under [[#Founders and co-founders|"Founders and cofounders" section]])
