===Astronomers and space explorers=== *[[William F. Ballhaus, Jr.]], B.S. 1967, M.S. 1968, Ph.D. 1971 â former director of [[NASA]]'s [[Ames Research Center]] , president and CEO of [[Aerospace Corporation]] (also listed in [[#Business and entrepreneurship|"Business and entrepreneurship" section]]) *[[Michael C. Malin]], B.A. (physics) 1967 â astronomer, principal investigator for the camera on [[Mars Global Surveyor]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phoenix.lpl.arizona.edu/malinMike.php|title=Mike Malin|publisher=[[University of Arizona]] [[Lunar and Planetary Laboratory]]}}</ref> [[MacArthur Fellow]],<ref name="CalTech2003_DistinguishedAlumniAwards">{{cite web|url=http://pr.caltech.edu/events/alumni_awards/03/|title=Caltech: 2003 Distinguished Alumni Awards|publisher=[[Caltech]]|year=2003}}</ref> founder and CEO of [[Malin Space Science Systems]], recipient of a [[NASA]] Exceptional Scientific Achievement Medal in 2002,<ref name="CalTech2003_DistinguishedAlumniAwards"/> recipient of the 2005 [[Carl Sagan Memorial Award]]<ref name="CalTech2003_DistinguishedAlumniAwards"/> *[[H. Paul Shuch]], Ph.D. 1990 â [[SETI]] scientist *[[Peter Smith (scientist)|Peter Smith]], B.S. 1969 â [[Principal investigator]] and project leader for the $420 million [[NASA]] robotic explorer ''[[Phoenix (spacecraft)|Phoenix]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uanews.org/node/19742|title=Peter Smith Named Thomas R. Brown Distinguished Chair in Integrative Science|author=[[University of Arizona]] University Communications|date=2008-03-18}}</ref> which physically confirmed the presence of water on the planet [[Mars]] for the first time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/phoenix/news/phoenix-20080731.html|title=NASA Spacecraft Confirms Martian Water, Mission Extended|date=2008-07-31|publisher=[[NASA]]}}</ref> *[[Joel Stebbins]], Ph.D. Physics 1903 â pioneered [[photoelectric]] [[photometry (astronomy)|photometry]] in astronomy, [[Royal Astronomical Society]] Gold Meal (1950),